---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

// Copy: EP's own edit pass, July 2026 — no longer the action-plan draft.
// Huawei is named with permission on all three levels: naming them as a
// client, describing the nature of the work, and citing the campaign's
// reach. EP is running the final wording past them before this ships.
// KY figures (Secretary General, €500k budget) match the profile page.
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Partners"
  lang="en"
  description="Partnership, speaking and advisory work with Esa-Pekka Mattila, T54 wheelchair racer, through LA 2028. What a partnership involves and what a season costs."
>
  <section class="partners-hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">Partners</p>
      <h1>Partnership,<br />speaking,<br />advisory<span class="accent-text">.</span></h1>
      <p class="lead">
        I am open to partners through LA 2028. This page sets out what
        that means in practice and what it costs, so a conversation can
        start from something concrete.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="narrative" id="partnership">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head reveal"><span class="idx mono">01</span><h2>Partnership</h2></div>
      <div class="prose reveal">
        <p>
          A season at world level costs around €20,000 before living
          costs: racing chairs, training camps, flights, physiotherapy,
          competition entry fees, equipment that wears out and gets
          replaced, and other costs such as coaching and expert help. My
          competitive plan runs from the World Championships in Tashkent
          in June 2027 through the European Championships in 2028, with
          Los Angeles 2028 as the last highlight of my career.
        </p>
        <p>
          My own channels are small and I won't pretend otherwise. They
          are open to a partner as well, they are simply not where the
          reach comes from. What I bring is the material: twenty years
          of competing at world level, a governance career running
          alongside it, and a track record of saying true things on
          camera. What a partner brings is distribution. When Huawei
          filmed the work we did together on wearable technology, the
          film reached over eight million views on their channels rather
          than mine. That is the division of labour I am proposing, and
          it has worked once already.
        </p>
        <p>
          Terms are defined case by case. I am looking for a small
          number of meaningful partners, not a shirt full of logos.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="narrative" id="speaking">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head reveal"><span class="idx mono">02</span><h2>Speaking</h2></div>
      <div class="prose reveal">
        <p>
          Keynotes, panels and workshops, in Finnish and English.
        </p>
        <p>
          Athlete representation where it actually matters: selection
          processes, funding disagreements, and balancing stakeholders
          who want different things. A federation cannot also be the
          athletes' representative in those rooms, however it is framed.
          Disability inclusion approached the same way. In both, naming
          the problem is the easy half; the work is building what
          resolves it.
        </p>
        <p>
          Alongside those: decision-making under constraint, and what
          elite sport systems can teach everyday working life and
          business.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="narrative" id="advisory">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head reveal"><span class="idx mono">03</span><h2>Advisory</h2></div>
      <div class="prose reveal">
        <p>
          Advisory work in wheelchair and assistive technology, such as
          with Huawei, taking a product feature from athlete feedback to
          shipped release. Also accessibility and governance questions,
          where lived experience, board experience and a business-law
          background merge. Earlier I was Secretary General of KY at
          Aalto University, with an annual budget over €500,000, which
          is where the operational understanding comes from.
        </p>
        <p>
          Always open, from a sparring session to a clearly defined
          project.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="partners-cta">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="rule-accent"></div>
      <p class="cta-line">Interested?</p>
      <a href="mailto:ep@esapekkamattila.com" class="cta-mail">ep@esapekkamattila.com</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .partners-hero {
    padding-top: clamp(140px, 20vh, 200px);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-5);
  }
  .partners-hero h1 {
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }
  .accent-text {
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .partners-hero .lead {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
    font-size: var(--text-lead);
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    max-width: 32rem;
  }

  .narrative {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    /* Clears the fixed nav when arriving via /partners#speaking */
    scroll-margin-top: 90px;
  }
  .narrative .prose p {
    font-size: clamp(1.0625rem, 1.5vw, 1.1875rem);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    max-width: 44rem;
  }
  .narrative .prose p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .sec-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 16px;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }
  .sec-head .idx {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
  }

  .partners-cta {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .cta-line {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: var(--text-h2);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: var(--line-tight);
  }
  .cta-mail {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }
</style>
